<DOCNO> AP880228-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the fertile missouri river bottom lands 
where the arikara hidatsa and mandan indians thrived for seven 
centuries are gone forever buried beneath the waters of lake 
sakakawea 
the 200milelong reservoir drove the indians onto higher less 
productive land sliced their reservation into isolated sections 
and is blamed for precipitating soaring unemployment and alcoholism 
the three tribes who say they were coerced into surrendering 
the bottom lands without just compensation as the lake filled 
behind garrison dam believe they have a chance this year to get 
1784 million that they and a special federal commission think 
they deserve 
the problem has been with us for 40 years the time is right 
for a resolution said tribal chairman edward lone fight 
the tribes which total about 7700 people are asking the 
states congressional delegation to introduce legislation that 
would give them 36 million a year for 50 years plus 4 percent 
interest on the unpaid balance of the settlement 
the money would come from federal hydropower revenues rather 
than the us treasury which tribal leaders believe should make 
the legislation more palatable to congress 
the bill also would fund municipal water projects on the 
reservation and authorize but not pay for replacement of a 
hospital and other facilities destroyed by the reservoir 
lone fight says the bill is something thats supportable in 
congress 
but the federal bureau of indian affairs opposes further 
compensation for the tribes rural electric cooperatives dont like 
the idea of dipping into hydropower revenues and members of the 
states congressional delegation have yet to support the bill 
we hope that something can be introduced this session but 
until we can find something that everyone feels comfortable with 
nothing can be introduced said mary jo vrem an aide to the 
senate select committee on indian affairs 
the tribes accepted 126 million from congress in 1950 but 
garrison dam was already built and lake sakakawea was forming when 
the money was offered the tribes and their supporters say the 
indians had no choice but to take the settlement 
when the indian people were negotiating for the best possible 
deal the water was up to their ankles and the offers were 
going down lone fight said 
when dam construction began in the 1940s 90 percent of the 
indians lived and farmed in the river valley as their ancestors 
had for seven centuries unemployment on the reservation was 
negligible 
today unemployment exceeds 50 percent and alcoholism is 
rampant problems that have been linked to the disruption caused by 
garrison dam about 3400 indians live on the reservation another 
4300 tribal members live elsewhere 
lake sakakawea is named for a shoshone guide who worked for the 
lewis and clark expedition up the missouri river in 1804 
in my 66 years i have seen a drastic change from being 
selfsufficent to being a very desperate economic situation said 
luther grinnell a tribal judge grinnell grew up on a family farm 
near elbowoods the reservations main town before it was inundated 
the tribes grew their own vegetables and cattle cut firewood 
from trees along the river and mined nearby coal deposits grinnell 
said 
we never heard of unemployment because everyone had their 
farms and those who had jobs didnt farm grinnell said 
a fivemember panel appointed by interior secretary donald hodel 
concluded in 1986 that the tribes were owed 178 million to 412 
million in compensation 
the joint tribal advisory committee agreed with indian claims 
that the lake destroyed their selfsufficient way of life and 
precipitated the tribes continuing social problems 
if the tribes get the settlement the money would be earmarked 
for programs such as work projects and alcohol treatment that 
would attack the reservations social ills lone fight said 
however in a recent meeting with tribal leaders assistant 
secretary for indian affairs ross swimmer claimed that the tribes 
have been adequately compensated through the federal services they 
receive 
swimmers position was characterized by ray cross an attorney 
for the tribes as disingenuous 
bureau of indian affairs officials will meet soon with members 
of north dakotas congressional delegation to discuss the tribes 
proposal bia spokesman carl shaw said 
</TEXT>
