<TEXT>
enrollment is up and the debt is down at 
fisk university where only a few years ago students shivered in 
unheated dormitories because the historically black private 
institution could not pay its gas bill 
as fisk winds down its celebration of black history month which 
included the dedication of a stamp honoring author james weldon 
johnson faculty and students also celebrated the universitys 
return from the brink of financial disaster 
when the nashville gas co cut off service in early 1984 until 
fisk paid a 170000 debt students brought space heaters to class 
and joined with faculty and staff members to raise funds to ensure 
the universitys survival the overall debt mounted to 41 
million but classes continued 
henry ponder appointed fisks president in july 1984 led the 
school on a course of austerity programs and aggressive 
fundraising 
when ponder was told for example that boiler repairs would 
cost 350000 he found a fisk alumnus a maintenance expert who 
did it for only 60000 
ponder acknowledged in a recent interview that things are better 
at fisk but added you have to get the public to understand that 
help is still needed to get the resources to move this institution 
to the forefront of educational institutions in this country 
i dont say that lightly thats where weve been and we will 
get back said ponder who said the school did not lower its 
academic standards during its financial troubles 
today debt at fisk has been reduced to 200000 and its 
endowment has reached 39 million an unrestricted gift of 13 
million by entertainer bill cosby in december 1986 gave the school 
a boost but officials say they have received substantial 
grassroots support too 
however three of the universitys 23 trustees announced friday 
that they will resign at the end of the school year one trustee 
said the resignations were related to the accountability of those 
charged with daytoday administration fisks financial aid 
director and assistant director were fired in december for 
allegedly failing to fill out forms to receive financial aid 
faculty salaries have increased 30 percent over the last three 
years to an average of 32000 for a tenured professor although 
still below the 35000 to 40000 ponder said is appropriate 
aggressive recruiting of students brought enrollment which 
dipped to 500 at one point up to 644 students in the 1988 spring 
semester an increase of 27 percent over the 1987 spring semester 
said harrison deshields director of the office of admissions and 
records 
bryon cobb a student from huntsville texas said fisks role 
in black history in america was important to him 
fisk introduced the black spiritual to the world it was 
active in the civil rights movement web dubois went to college 
here cobb said 
in addition he said my understanding is that a degree from 
fisk is as respected as one from harvard 
the financial crisis at the school had some positive benefits 
for the fisk community said roland hayes robinson now a graduate 
student 
the student body handled the crisis well we shared space 
heaters it united us we were able to confront a problem and come 
through it robinson sid 
the university founded in 1867 by the freedmens bureau during 
reconstruction is no stranger to struggle in fact the campus was 
purchased with 150000 raised by the colleges jubilee singers 
during a european tour in the 1870s 
the earnings of the singers whose tours still bring 60000 a 
year to fisk also paid for building jubilee hall whose exterior 
was recently restored with a 150000 federal grant 
james weldon johnson a poet who was a diplomat and an early 
organizer of the national association for the advancement of 
colored people was a professor at fisk in the early 1930s web 
dubois a philosopher and writer who graduated from fisk in 1888 
also helped found the naacp and was the first black to earn a 
doctorate from harvard 
i think students are attracted here because it has the 
reputation of a good community when they get here they find out 
we have a dynamic science faculty and many of our students go to 
medical and dental schools ponder said about 60 percent of fisk 
graduates enroll for postgraduate study 
revais mitchell executive assistant to the president and a 
history professor said fisks financial problems mirrored those of 
other liberal arts college but were worse 
in the 1960s and 1970s the philosophy of supporting a liberal 
arts education dried up and the interest shifted to business 
degrees mitchell said 
but mitchell said the quality of education at fisk has never 
suffered and that peeling paint and cold classrooms dont mean poor 
academics 
i try to tell my students that there has always been an 
element of suffering in the tradition of black education he said 
</TEXT>
