<TEXT>
three mexican nationals including a former 
mexican police detective charged in the torturemurder of a us 
drug agent were convicted of conspiring to murder a us customs 
agent 
the charges grew out of a series of meetings with an undercover 
investigator in which defendant raul lopez alvarez offered to 
murder the customs agent for a 25000 fee no killing took place 
lopez 29 who also faces charges in the 1985 slaying of us 
drug enforcement administration agent enrique camarena was 
convicted friday of conspiracy to murder a federal agent and 
conspiracy to kidnap a federal agent 
two men lopez hired in mexico to assist him carlos quintero 
maldonado 25 and fabian jimenez martinez 22 also were convicted 
in the conspiracy quintero was acquitted on a charge that he 
traveled to the united states from mexico to carry out the murder 
plot 
the men could receive life imprisonment sentencing was 
scheduled for april 18 before us district judge pamela m rymer 
lawyers for the defendants had argued that lopez and the two men 
he hired never intended to carry out the murder but had planned 
all along to stage a ripoff of the undercover drug agent with 
whom they were negotiating they believed that the undercover agent 
was a narcotics dealer 
lopez a former homicide investigator for the mexican state 
judicial police told undercover agents he was an enforcer for 
the powerful narcotics organization of rafael caro quintero and 
ernesto fonseca carrillo and had a direct role in camarenas 
abduction and torture 
in 12 hours of government tapes presented as evidence lopez 
bragged about his knowledge of camarenas torture and promised to 
repeat it on the customs agent 
if it was part of a scam they oversold it too much said 
jury foreman david armas 28 a postal worker from alhambra 
especially when they talked about killing someone you looked at 
their faces and they showed no remorse 
nine people have been indicted in the camarena case two of whom 
will be tried with lopez caro and fonseca are jailed in mexico 
city in connection with the case lopez had been charged in mexico 
with the camarena murder but was later released 
</TEXT>
