<TEXT>
about 1000 people trying to buck the chinese 
system of assigned jobs for life gathered sunday at the opening of 
beijings first citywide labor market 
a mostly young crowd bundled up in heavy greatcoats peered at 
job description posters lining the street and discussed work 
opportunities with representatives of 22 factories and companies 
who manned desks inside the labor exchange center 
the center said deputy chief zhao fenyong was set up by the 
city labor bureau to carry out the government policy of allowing 
people to find jobs more suitable to their needs and skills 
those who pay a fee of 27 cents will have their names placed on 
the centers computerized list and receive help in finding a new 
job he said 
liu wanxin of the tienma service co which supplies tourist 
items to department stores said many people want to find new work 
closer to their homes 
others just dont like their present jobs he said adding 
that his company found seven prospective new employees sunday 
morning 
li hongjun 34 said she was applying for a job with a beijing 
wine company because it has night shifts allowing her to care for 
a sick sister during the day she said she could also take a bus to 
the winery rather than commute by bicycle as she does to her 
current job 
a personnel officer at qinghua university which is looking for 
nine cooks electricians drivers and other workers said factory 
workers are attracted to the schools long summer and winter 
holidays many said wang jingxiang also want their children to 
attend the excellent kindergarten and primary schools run by the 
university 
since the 1949 communist takeover chinese have had little 
choice in determining their career 
under a system known as fen pei chinese were assigned a job 
for life from which they could not be fired but neither could they 
leave 
high school and elementary school graduates were assigned work 
in local businesses or if they come from the countryside were 
generally returned to the land to farm with the rest of their 
family 
college graduates a scarce resource here were sent anywhere in 
the country that needed them a student majoring in english 
literature at prestigious beijing university could for example 
wind up in barren qinghai province teaching english to barely 
literate peasants 
but in recent years cracks have appeared in chinas iron rice 
bowl as the country has sought to speed its economic development 
the chinese government has recognized that its traditional labor 
system has deadened worker creativity and kept workers from fully 
using their talents 
it also has split families especially those of the educated 
classes indeed it is not unusual for couples with college 
educations to be assigned jobs in different provinces thousands of 
miles away from one another 
as a result china has begun loosening restrictions on 
jobhopping and encouraging the 20 million people who have gone off 
on their own to set up small private businesses 
however the work units to which each chinese is assigned still 
regard employees as the property of the unit and often refuse a job 
transfer or exact compensation for the loss of a worker 
engineers scientists and other trained people in particular 
have had difficulty leaving their old jobs because of their value 
to the work unit 
that creates the ironic condition that the better one does ones 
job here the less of a chance one has to leave it for something 
better 
its true that if a person has a position of responsibility it 
will be more difficult for him to change jobs said the centers 
zhao but if his work unit refuses to let him go we will do what 
we can to help including assist in finding a replacement 
similar labor markets have appeared at the city district level 
in beijing but the center that opened sunday is the first to cover 
the entire city 
illegal work markets have also sprung up in beijing and in 
several other chinese cities their purpose generally is not to 
help employed people find a new job but to help unemployed 
peasants enter the urban labor force allowing them to abandon the 
difficult life in chinas countryside 
zhao said the citywide labor market will also stay open in the 
evenings and on sundays to accommodate people who have difficulty 
getting away from their jobs to look for new ones 
