archaeologists said sunday they discovered the 
remains of a roman amphitheater 15 feet below londons financial 
district in one of the most important finds in britain this century 
historians had been looking for londons amphitheater for 300 
years amphitheaters were used for weapons training and military 
parades as well as fights with animals and gladiatorial combat 
archaeologists from the museum of london uncovered the eastern 
end of the amphitheaters stone walls during excavations going on 
since last july said john maloney the museums excavations 
officer in an interview with the observer weekly 
the corporation of london which administers london city gave 
the museum 176000 to dig on the site next to the medieval 
guildhall where the corporation meets 
an art gallery and an office building has been planned for the 
amphitheaters site 
the observer reported that the corporation will talk with the 
archaeologists and architects this week to discuss preservation of 
the uncovered amphitheater remains 
a clash could develop if the corporation wants to rebury the 
site and proceed with the art gallery and offices the observer 
said 
london was founded by the romans who called it londinium the 
romans stayed in britain from ad 43 to 410 
the excavators think the amphitheater was built between ad 70 
and 140 during the heyday of roman london 
corroded coins found on the site may help to date the ruin more 
exactly 
the center of the amphitheater is under the open courtyard in 
front of guildhall almost all the area where the seats and walls 
would have been is under guildhall itself the art gallery site and 
neighboring buildings 
the excavators say the amphitheater was oval shaped 100 yards 
from east to west and 80 yards north to south 
that is small compared with roman amphitheaters found in 
southern france and italy but about the same size as four others 
in england at cirencester chester chichester and silchester 
