<TEXT>
lisa carlson borrowed a truck to take her 
husbands body to the crematory after he shot himself in 1981 in 
the early hours of the morning she could think clearly enough only 
to know she didnt have the money to pay a funeral home 
his ashes are buried in the garden behind their country home 
the spot marked by a slab of granite on which she etched his name 
john brackett with a pocket knife 
she regrets only that she didnt share the intimate farewell 
with her husbands mother and the couples children 
now carlson has written a book to help other people make their 
own funeral arrangements she began writing it after her current 
husband stephen and his three brothers buried their mother in a 
pine box atop a ridge 
its very easy to understand why people give it away to a 
funeral home and indeed if i had had the money i would have 
given away a very special opportunity carlson said during a 
recent interview at her home 
her book caring for your own dead includes a directory of 
each states laws on funeral arrangements cremation and home 
burial a glossary of terms and instructions on completing a death 
certificate it also includes a listing of medical schools that 
accept body donations 
i really tried to take the mystery out of body disposition 
carlson said 
many states allow funerals to be handled privately but carlson 
said there may be obstacles to obtaining needed information on 
short notice including some funeral directors reluctant to offer 
prices over the telephone and local officials unaccustomed to the 
idea she credits many in the funeral industry for their help 
during her nine months of researching the book 
she found that anyone in vermont can do a home burial as long as 
technical requirements involving the death certificate are met if 
the burial is to be on private property it must be away from power 
lines and water and may be subject to local zoning restrictions 
the town clerk keeps a map of private burial plots 
according to carlson a cremation could cost as little as 130 
including a permit transportation and a box would add to the cost 
the professional services and cost of the casket are two of 
the major expenses carlson said 
in 1987 the average cost of a funeral including professional 
services and a casket was 2935 according to an industry 
newsletter funeral service insider 
carlson took on her husbands funeral first from financial 
necessity but then she realized that not only was it all right 
it became clear to me that i needed to do it 
one funeral director whom she had interviewed for the book 
called her after his 7yearold son died 
he didnt realize until afterwards how important it was for 
him to be involved personally she said 
most states do not limit the family in caring for their dead 
but some prohibit home burial and limit the scattering of ashes 
her book says about 80 percent of the 500 crematories carlson 
contacted across the country will accept a body from someone other 
than a funeral director 
no state requires a body to be embalmed in every case but many 
require it if a person died of a contagious disease the book says 
in alaska a body may not be closed after an autopsy in most of 
california burial must be in an established cemetery colorado has 
no state licensing requirements for funeral directors so anyone 
may handle a funeral 
in new england according to carlsons book there are limits on 
private funerals and home burial in new hampshire connecticut 
massachusetts and new york 
other states where the familys involvement in funeral 
arrangements may be limited are indiana louisiana massachusetts 
michigan minnesota nebraska nevada new jersey ohio and west 
virginia she says 
