<TEXT>
high maple syrup prices after two abysmal 
sugaring seasons have prompted more people to tap more trees as the 
sap starts running this year new hampshires agriculture chief 
says 
new hampshire syrup sells for as much as 43 a gallon nearly 
double the price before backtoback bad seasons but demand has 
not lagged said agriculture commissioner stephen taylor 
whats really kept it up there is packaging in ever smaller 
packages we talk about the price per gallon but nobody ever buys a 
gallon of syrup anymore taylor said in an interview last week 
the 150000 gallons of maple syrup sold annually in new 
hampshire most of it in gift shops and country stores comes in 
jugs as small as a pint or less taylor said but not all of it 
comes from new hampshire 
theres some new production coming out of the woodwork in 
ontario ohio indiana that is sold bulk to packagers in new 
hampshire taylor said but we have the aura a geographic 
chauvinism favoring new england maple syrup 
state law ensures that if you call it new hampshire maple 
syrup it has to be made in new hampshire he said 
taylor estimated there are 400 commercial maple syrup producers 
in new hampshire and 1000 backyard farmtype people 
we will tap a lot more trees this year as a result of high 
prices he said sales of equipment and tubing indicate a lot 
more people are getting in this year 
sap runs when temperatures dip below freezing at night and rise 
to the 40s in the day conditions that began to occur in some 
places earlier this month 
new hampshire produced 100000 gallons of syrup in its best 
year 1984 but during the last two years warm weather day and 
night predominated and production was around 30 percent of normal 
technology is revolutionizing the sugaring industry taylor 
said he estimated more than 80 percent of taps this year will feed 
into tubing that carries sap directly to evaporators and other 
processing equipment rather than into buckets 
taylor says higher syrup prices staying around for awhile 
regardless of how good this season is 
if we go in with cupboard bare no carryover syrup from last 
season prices will be substantially higher than previous years 
even with a bumper crop 
a coowner of the states largest syrup producer bascoms sugar 
house in acworth said she was puzzled that demand has remained 
stable despite the price 
i dont buy maple syrup i cant explain it liz bascom 
said we made less gallons at a higher price last year and we 
came out about the same 
