<TEXT>
chrysler corps plans to close a wisconsin 
assembly plant and its admission that it might sell its acustar 
inc parts subsidiary are fueling worker anger and distrust as the 
two sides head into this summers national contract talks 
chryslers parts operations were grouped into the subsidiary 
last spring but most of acustars 28000 workers have been with 
chrysler since it battled back from the brink of bankruptcy early 
in the decade when they granted concessions to keep the company 
afloat 
chrysler workers think the potential sale now that the no 3 
carmaker is again earning billiondollar profits indicates they 
wont be able to trust the company in the contract negotiations 
more than 1000 workers vented their anger last week outside 
chryslers highland park headquarters waving signs and shouting 
strike strike at an emotional rally led by united auto 
workers vice president marc stepp 
one sign read concessions in 79 the shaft in 88 
stepp who will lead negotiations with chrysler said he will 
give uaw locals permission to strike on a plantbyplant basis 
based on local disagreements but because of the acustar issue 
workers also are threatening to stop participating with 
management on a variety of joint programs like quality control 
the acustar controversy comes on top of chryslers announcement 
that it will close its assembly plant at kenosha wis this year 
and idle 5500 workers chrysler acquired the plant last year when 
it bought american motors 
state and local officials charged that chrysler had promised to 
keep the plant running for five years wisconsins governor 
threatened to sue and last week the uaw went to court on its own 
in an attempt to keep the plant open 
many of these workers gave concessions and made considerable 
sacrifices to help the company make it said harley shaiken a 
labor and technology expert at the university of california at san 
diego 
they thought they were investing in their future and acustar 
represents an uncertain future if its sold chrysler 
underestimated the strength of the reaction and the fact that it 
has spread beyond acustar workers and affected the entire 
company he said 
one of those workers is roger fitzpatrick a member of uaw local 
1435 at an acustar machining plant in perrysburg ohio 
yes we will strike he said at last weeks rally 
whatever it takes to keep them from selling it 
were also going to shut down all quality meetings anything 
thats joint with management and the union we will not attend 
none of them 
chrysler vice president baron bates said the company is still 
weighing the acustar sale he said the workers anger and their 
future under a new owner will be factors in the decision 
bates said chrysler views the bitter responses to the kenosha 
closing and the backlash against the acustar sale as two separate 
issues rather than a snowballing deterioration in labor relations 
there is also tension over chryslers continuing efforts to get 
more work out of fewer employees 
whats irritating workers is not simply acustar that has 
served as a lightning rod for other issues shaiken said 
theres a lot of pressure in chrysler plants 
workers see another threat with the sale chrysler could become 
the first big three automaker to follow the japanese model of 
treating parts and assembly workers as two distinct classes 
if acustar is sold its workers face lower wages and benefits 
and probably wont receive the job protections the uaw won in the 
threeyear contracts negotiated last fall with ford motor co and 
general motors corp 
chrysler has until sept 14 when its current threeyear 
contract expires to sell acustar and restructure itself as a 
japanesestyle maker that builds engines and transmissions 
assembles vehicles and depends on outside suppliers for all other 
parts 
after the 70000worker contract expires chrysler almost 
certainly will have to accept the pattern contract established at 
ford and gm last fall that makes layoffs for reasons other than 
slow sales costly and difficult 
the contract also discourages moving work to outside suppliers 
the uaw successfully resisted attempts by gm and ford to 
establish separate pay and benefit scales for parts workers last 
fall and doesnt want a precedent that would encourage them to try 
again in 1990 
the stakes here go well beyond chrysler shaiken said 
the pay of chrysler workers who gave concessions from 1979 
through 1983 returned to parity with workers at ford and gm in a 
1984 contract that included a basepay increase in 1987 auto 
workers earn an average 1215 an hour in wages and 810 an hour 
in benefits 
