<DOCNO> AP880228-0096 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
world merchandise trade grew more quickly last 
year than in 1986 and barring economic upheavals should expand at 
least as quickly this year a report by a world trade group said 
monday 
the crash of world stock markets last october does not appear to 
have had an immediate adverse impact on global commerce said 
the secretariat of the general agreement on tariffs and trade 
early estimates show the volume of world merchandise trade rose 
by 4 percent last year compared to 35 percent in 1986 the world 
trade agencys analysts said 
barring a further major upheaval in financial markets or a 
serious recession in the united states it should grow at least as 
rapidly in 1988 they said 
last september gatt had predicted only about 35 percent growth 
for 1987 
the report expressed concern about trade imbalances among the 
worlds largest economies also third world debt and protectionist 
pressures still burden the world economy it said 
but consumer and investor confidence has survived the stock 
crash better than analysts forecasted immediately after the crisis 
the report said 
the improvement in the outlook for trade in recent months 
means that all other things being equal the risk of a recession 
in 1988 is smaller gatt chief economist richard blackhurst said 
the value of merchandise exports rose 155 percent in 1987 to a 
new record of 245 billion partly reflecting the depreciation of 
the us dollar and higher prices for crude oil and other 
commodities the report said 
manufactured goods led the expansion with a 5 percent rise in 
volume up from 35 percent in 1986 farm exports rebounded to an 
estimated 4 percent rise after a decline of 1 percent the report 
said 
reduced petroleum trade helped push trade volume in mining 
products down 1 percent 
imports by industrialized market economies remained the 
strongest force in world trade expansion though growth slowed to 5 
percent from 85 percent in 1986 the report said 
another factor cited was fast growth in asian economies such as 
hong kong south korea singapore and taiwan these countries have 
become significant buyers of manufactured goods on world markets as 
well as exporters gatt said 
export growth in developing countries slowed to 6 percent from 9 
percent in 1986 but remained more vigorous than in other parts of 
the world 
the report noted improved trade performance by a group of 15 
heavily indebted countries including 10 in latin america 
statecontrolled economies like china and the soviet bloc 
expanded their trade less than other countries particularly 
because they squeezed imports to adjust to lower export revenues 
from fuels and debt service requirements the report said 
the gatt includes about 100 member nations and was set up after 
world war ii it is both an agreement and a forum for removing 
trade barriers and ensuring the free movement of goods around the 
world it is administered by a permanent commission by the same 
name in geneva 
</TEXT>
