war not just with pizza but with all kinds of homedelivered 
food said charlie henderson vice president of marketing for 
godfathers pizza an omaha nebbased division of pillsbury inc 
people are timeshort and dollarrich said henderson whose 
company is shrinking sitdown areas in its new restaurants and 
mobilizing larger road forces they dont want to eat out 
theyre more than willing to pay to have it brought to their houses 
and i dont see it ending 
the explosion of convenience food in all its frozen and 
homedelivered variations can be traced to two late80s phenomena 
said stephen carnes managing director of research for the 
brokerage firm of piper jaffray amp hopwood 
carnes said his companys research shows 65 percent of us 
homes now have microwave ovens and 55 percent of all married women 
work households typically are short on time for cooking and long 
on money to pay others to do it 
but restaurants have shortcomings as an alternative to kitchen 
toil henderson and others note costs can be high and theres 
usually a wait 
moreover food industry analysts say that in an age of vcrs 
staying at home cocooning as its been dubbed is becoming 
an end in itself 
grocery stores around the country have scurried to meet the 
demand with wider offerings of prepared and semiprepared dinners 
the choices range from macaroni and cheese on the low end to london 
broil and rattlesnake at the top 
even a drive to the grocery store can sometimes be too strenuous 
for the workweary said peter flatow president of the new york 
market research company brainreserve inc 
the goal is delivering a nice dinner to them the challenge is 
overcoming high cost and logistics 
dominos pizza has done it now all youve got to do is get 
veal marsala there and youve got it flatow said the need is 
there nobody has fulfilled it yet 
a general mills spokesman would not discuss the order inn 
venture citing competitive factors local analysts say it has been 
under way for roughly six months 
industry watchers describe it as a logical step for general 
mills which also owns the red lobster yorks and olive garden 
restaurant chains based in golden valley a minneapolis suburb 
the company also has takeout experience it recently sold its chain 
of leann chins chinese restaurants which offered both sitdown 
and eatathome meals 
order inn menus being dropped off at twin cities homes in recent 
months promise free delivery usually in less than 20 minutes both 
lunches and dinners are available seven days a week 
the menu offers four selections in the appetizers and salad 
section including chilled shrimp and popcorn chicken two 
sandwiches are available and five entrees ranging from 575 for 
lasagna to 1095 for prime rib whitechocolate macadamia nut 
cheesecake highlights the three dessert choices 
the menus include detailed instructions on reheating in a 
microwave or oven and a questionnaire asking what was ordered and 
how the food and service ranked 
no verdict is in sight on the order inn but experts say general 
mills seems to have the right idea 
i dont think theres any question there will be more to 
follow said craig carver senior vice president of the 
minneapolis brokerage firm of dain bosworth 
a chief obstacle to success is keeping costs under control with 
pizza for example gasoline drivers insurance and other costs 
take a 3 to 4 slice out of a 10 pizza godfathers henderson 
says 
an extra hurdle for order inn is the daily gamble on how many 
orders will be placed for each item leftovers must be disposed of 
at days end general mills spokesman craig shulstad confirmed 
whatever the future of the experiment industry watchers predict 
scratch cooking will become ever more a recreational weekend 
pastime and restaurants they say should beware 
its really a fight for share of stomach carver said 
